    pearls: ["Thyroglobulin (Tg) is the PRIMARY surveillance marker after total thyroidectomy — it should be UNDETECTABLE; a rising Tg indicates recurrence; always check TgAb simultaneously (TgAb can cause falsely low Tg)","Rising TgAb may indicate recurrence EVEN IF Tg appears low — TgAb in immunometric assays causes falsely low Tg results; trend TgAb over time","Dynamic risk stratification: patients are RE-CLASSIFIED based on treatment response at each follow-up — a high-risk patient with excellent response can be reclassified to lower surveillance intensity; conversely, a low-risk patient with rising Tg is reclassified to higher intensity","TSH suppression goals differ by risk: low-risk with excellent response → TSH 0.5-2.0 (near-normal); high-risk or incomplete response → TSH <0.1 (full suppression) — over-suppression in low-risk patients causes unnecessary harm (AF, osteoporosis)","Neck ultrasound is the most important imaging modality for surveillance — more sensitive than clinical exam for detecting recurrent/persistent cervical disease","FDG-PET/CT is most useful for 'thyroglobulin-positive, RAI-negative' disease — indicates tumor de-differentiation (loss of iodine avidity); this defines RAI-refractory disease requiring systemic therapy","Levothyroxine must be taken consistently on an empty stomach — calcium, iron, PPIs, and antacids all reduce absorption and affect TSH levels"],
